1
00:00:01,887 --> 00:00:28,722
Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samasambuddhasa Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samasambuddhasa Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samasambuddhasa

2
00:00:29,106 --> 00:00:33,700
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:36,649 --> 00:00:48,146
Just an opportunity really, isn't it, to revise our understanding of the Bodhidhamma according to a certain Bhikkhu Bodhidhamma.

4
00:00:48,167 --> 00:00:57,680
So, just trying to put it in the context also of New Year and a time for resolutions, things like that.

5
00:00:59,243 --> 00:01:05,171
An opportunity to look back and to...

6
00:01:05,152 --> 00:01:07,894
have some way of reflecting upon our lives.

7
00:01:11,379 --> 00:01:17,867
I suppose it's good just to remind ourselves of this basic psychology that the Buddha teaches us.

8
00:01:19,269 --> 00:01:30,542
We can start really by seeing that he gives us a sort of cross-section of every moment and also what happens in process, what happens over a period of time.

9
00:01:30,561 --> 00:01:32,965
So that cross-section he called the five

10
00:01:33,367 --> 00:01:49,805
the five aggregates and the one that's interesting specifically these days is cognition which is the fifth one as you all know cognition is momentary

11
00:01:50,933 --> 00:02:04,311
If we were to really see what was happening now, what we would experience as a sort of stroboscopic universe, it would be arising and passing away at tremendous speed.

12
00:02:05,753 --> 00:02:16,467
These are like little photographs that are caught by consciousness, an act of cognition.

13
00:02:18,658 --> 00:02:25,497
It's only because it's happening at this enormous speed that it gives us a sense of flow, a sense of continuity.

14
00:02:26,360 --> 00:02:31,335
And of course, from a point of view of delusion, it's easy for us to identify with that.

15
00:02:31,854 --> 00:02:33,377
I am the one.

16
00:02:34,038 --> 00:02:38,302
I am that process of knowing because I always seem to be there.

17
00:02:39,503 --> 00:02:41,406
And whenever I'm knowing something, it's always me.

18
00:02:44,270 --> 00:02:49,096
Even if I lose myself in an absorption, I still come out and say, oh, that was me.

19
00:02:50,176 --> 00:02:57,846
So there's that problem of identity which we'll come to in terms of the flow of our psychology.

20
00:02:58,652 --> 00:03:05,621
And what it catches, what this moment of cognition always catches, are these four other aggregates in a singular moment.

21
00:03:06,342 --> 00:03:09,625
So there's always the body, rupa.

22
00:03:10,545 --> 00:03:15,451
I translate it as the body, but it's not at a subtle level, it's not the body itself.

23
00:03:16,092 --> 00:03:19,917
What we know of the body, what we can experience of the body, is quite minimal.

24
00:03:20,298 --> 00:03:23,540
I mean, what do you know about your big toenail?

25
00:03:23,561 --> 00:03:24,162
See, very little.

26
00:03:24,842 --> 00:03:26,905
I mean, you can feel it, you can see the color of it.

27
00:03:27,356 --> 00:03:28,657
But you've never been it, have you?

28
00:03:29,459 --> 00:03:30,741
Have you ever been a toenail?

29
00:03:33,544 --> 00:03:35,126
It's not something you can absorb into.

30
00:03:36,507 --> 00:03:37,127
It's there.

31
00:03:37,247 --> 00:03:40,292
And of course, we're quite happy to cut it off when it gets a bit too long.

32
00:03:41,453 --> 00:03:42,914
But we don't think we're losing a bit of me.

33
00:03:43,375 --> 00:03:45,258
At least I don't.

34
00:03:45,277 --> 00:03:50,943
I don't go through a burial ceremony whenever I cut my toenail off.

35
00:03:52,224 --> 00:03:53,567
Or any nail, when I think about it.

36
00:03:55,183 --> 00:04:05,811
So, when you investigate what this body is, I think it's quite surprising how little we're aware of what's going on at any given time.

37
00:04:06,472 --> 00:04:11,504
You know, whether it's an organ such as the liver or the blood flow,

38
00:04:12,211 --> 00:04:14,813
or the passage of, I think it's red corpuscles, isn't it?

39
00:04:14,993 --> 00:04:18,759
Out of the marrow of the bone, through the bone, into the bloodstream.

40
00:04:18,778 --> 00:04:20,581
I haven't a clue what's going on.

41
00:04:20,680 --> 00:04:23,824
In fact, I would have been quite happy in ignorance.

42
00:04:24,725 --> 00:04:26,187
It's just reading these silly books.

43
00:04:26,788 --> 00:04:33,516
I've opened up this realization that I haven't a clue, generally speaking, what's going on in my body.

44
00:04:33,737 --> 00:04:34,899
I know when it goes wrong, of course.

45
00:04:35,500 --> 00:04:37,461
I mean, when it's okay, it feels all right.

46
00:04:37,502 --> 00:04:39,725
There's a general feeling of wellness.

47
00:04:39,745 --> 00:04:41,307
When it goes off, I get very worried.

48
00:04:43,766 --> 00:04:49,293
So, when the Buddha talks about the body, yes, he's talking about the way we relate to the body.

49
00:04:51,194 --> 00:04:55,178
And we can see that there's three delusive ways of relating.

50
00:04:55,478 --> 00:05:00,444
One of them is through a sense of disgust with the body, you know, not being happy with the way it smells and does things.

51
00:05:01,704 --> 00:05:07,451
And he gives us these exercises of looking at the disgusting nature of the body.

52
00:05:08,911 --> 00:05:10,533
That's not to make us more disgusted.

53
00:05:11,863 --> 00:05:14,512
That's to make us overcome disgust.

54
00:05:14,533 --> 00:05:16,860
That's to make us see the body as it really is.

55
00:05:17,100 --> 00:05:18,745
It's an animal, for heaven's sake.

56
00:05:19,047 --> 00:05:21,675
There's no difference between us and those sheep that you see out in the field.

57
00:05:21,735 --> 00:05:22,778
They've got everything we've got.

58
00:05:23,562 --> 00:05:24,303
Just different shapes.

59
00:05:26,139 --> 00:05:35,949
And it's going beyond the sense of disgust, which is all about, really, the way we see ourselves, the way we perceive the world.

60
00:05:36,009 --> 00:05:39,052
So if something is smelly, for instance, we think it's bad.

61
00:05:39,653 --> 00:05:40,053
But it's not.

62
00:05:40,074 --> 00:05:40,673
It's just smelly.

63
00:05:41,314 --> 00:05:41,694
That's all right.

64
00:05:43,317 --> 00:05:49,403
And then there's this business of the way we look, which is, of course, a social construct, whether you're beautiful or not.

65
00:05:51,564 --> 00:05:53,185
And that can cause us all sorts of misery.

66
00:05:53,206 --> 00:05:54,848
It causes people terrible misery.

67
00:05:55,468 --> 00:05:58,355
pimples on the end of your nose can be the cause of deep depression.

68
00:06:00,158 --> 00:06:04,547
So it's a case of recognizing also that the body is just a body.

69
00:06:04,987 --> 00:06:10,620
It doesn't have to be beautiful at all to perform its tasks.

70
00:06:11,100 --> 00:06:13,225
It's just an organism.

71
00:06:14,807 --> 00:06:21,757
And the other thing is, of course, when we investigate our relationship with the body, is that we've invested a tremendous amount of our happiness in it.

72
00:06:22,658 --> 00:06:28,247
So that if we, for instance, start going blind or deaf, it's a horror story for us.

73
00:06:30,088 --> 00:06:39,802
Meaning we might know that from people who are disabled, that eventually makes no difference to our quality of life if we approach the situation with acceptance.

74
00:06:40,223 --> 00:06:44,730
But that doesn't undermine the fact that getting there is very painful.

75
00:06:47,392 --> 00:06:52,620
Even this, see I've got this pain in my tooth, it was right at the back of my mouth, nobody would ever know about it.

76
00:06:53,360 --> 00:06:54,983
But I'm very worried, see.

77
00:06:56,564 --> 00:07:01,250
I might have to have it taken out, then I've only got one gnasher on the top.

78
00:07:01,271 --> 00:07:02,973
Well, that's terrible, isn't it?

79
00:07:02,992 --> 00:07:07,538
I mean, if I lose that, I've had it, I'm going to have to wear one of those plastic things in my mouth.

80
00:07:07,798 --> 00:07:08,220
Terrible.

81
00:07:09,752 --> 00:07:23,274
So when you look at the body, Buddha is saying all that, but that actually is, in a sense, the more gross, the more obvious, not so much gross, the more obvious part of our relationship to the body.

82
00:07:24,937 --> 00:07:30,326
But when we really investigate what is it we, you know, what are the building blocks upon which we

83
00:07:31,218 --> 00:07:34,324
Know the body and you actually go into your meditation.

84
00:07:34,725 --> 00:07:37,673
I mean, the obvious one that I normally talk about is pain, isn't it?

85
00:07:37,692 --> 00:07:40,661
Because when you go into pain, there's no pain there at all.

86
00:07:40,721 --> 00:07:49,682
What you've got is tightness or pressure, burning, prickling, all sorts of sensations, but there's no pain as such.

87
00:07:50,269 --> 00:07:57,122
And then you realize that actually all we can know of the body is its sensation, the sensations that are coming from the body.

88
00:07:57,661 --> 00:08:05,355
And from that we build up these concepts, emotional concepts too, like pain.

89
00:08:05,495 --> 00:08:11,586
Pain is not just a simple medical description, it's actually something you feel.

90
00:08:13,540 --> 00:08:26,571
So, when we go into that first heap, that first aggregate of the body, the Buddha is actually pointing to the fact that it's the point where the mind

91
00:08:26,973 --> 00:08:28,134
is touching the body.

92
00:08:28,153 --> 00:08:29,976
The mind is against the body, right?

93
00:08:30,076 --> 00:08:39,528
What it can actually cognize that we have to begin to see that that is actually only these momentary sensations.

94
00:08:39,548 --> 00:08:44,533
And these momentary sensations are only momentary because that's the way cognition behaves.

95
00:08:46,015 --> 00:08:49,360
It just catches every moment like that.

96
00:08:49,639 --> 00:08:52,744
Like the old films, like the old film reels.

97
00:08:55,659 --> 00:09:00,927
And then from that, we create our sanya, which is our perception.

98
00:09:00,947 --> 00:09:03,210
So these perceptions are memories.

99
00:09:03,370 --> 00:09:04,772
That's our memory, perceptions.

100
00:09:05,413 --> 00:09:09,899
And at first, they're very simple, red, blue, box, and all that sort of stuff.

101
00:09:09,919 --> 00:09:12,943
But they eventually build up into concepts.

102
00:09:14,144 --> 00:09:21,195
They're ways in which then we start looking at the world through the history that we've had with it.

103
00:09:22,272 --> 00:09:23,072
you see, the sanya.

104
00:09:24,815 --> 00:09:35,908
These sanya, you can see them as basic perceptions which lie at the back of the slow growth of concepts.

105
00:09:36,028 --> 00:09:41,215
But as you get a concept, it becomes a sanya because that's the way you perceive the world.

106
00:09:41,255 --> 00:09:47,023
You're perceiving the world through a particular concept.

107
00:09:47,243 --> 00:09:51,368
And again, in our meditation, we're trying to go beyond that by

108
00:09:51,922 --> 00:10:02,554
the process of getting back down to the initial sensations that we have in the body, grounding ourselves in the body.

109
00:10:03,316 --> 00:10:11,506
So, feelings, sensations, they're not made up by the mind, they're actually a direct experience of it.

110
00:10:11,527 --> 00:10:17,254
So, when you're walking around the meadow there and you can feel your boots sinking into the mud,

111
00:10:18,347 --> 00:10:24,573
It's a case of actually feeling what the sensation is of sinking into mud.

112
00:10:25,575 --> 00:10:26,936
And that's not made up.

113
00:10:26,975 --> 00:10:29,278
That's not some conceptual idea.

114
00:10:29,318 --> 00:10:32,442
That's a direct experience of sinking in the mud.

115
00:10:32,861 --> 00:10:34,724
And while I remember, there's all those moles out there.

116
00:10:36,926 --> 00:10:39,908
And I'm walking around thinking I shall sink my boot into a molehill.

117
00:10:42,171 --> 00:10:43,351
Stop Morris reappearing.

118
00:10:43,952 --> 00:10:45,333
We've got a rational, haven't we?

119
00:10:46,596 --> 00:10:51,586
So those are those sensations, sañña, perceptions, you see.

120
00:10:51,606 --> 00:11:00,583
And then on top of that we have a whole, a sort of second layer of experience that we call feelings, vedana.

121
00:11:01,065 --> 00:11:04,250
And this is what we feel in the body.

122
00:11:04,450 --> 00:11:16,331
These vedana are made up of these basic sensations that we have, but they're being described as either pleasant, unpleasant, or neutral.

123
00:11:16,912 --> 00:11:24,124
And as soon as we do that, you see, in any given moment, we're living in a dualistic world in terms of feeling.

124
00:11:24,365 --> 00:11:28,652
It's either pleasant, unpleasant, or some shade in between.

125
00:11:28,986 --> 00:11:35,794
Even neutral sensations, when you really investigate them, will have a shade of being pleasant or unpleasant.

126
00:11:35,815 --> 00:11:36,495
So that's the mind.

127
00:11:36,556 --> 00:11:42,822
I mean, that's the way, that's a given, you might say, the Veda.

128
00:11:44,225 --> 00:11:51,793
And remember that these sensations are both physical, coming from the body itself, like pain, like pleasure, but it's also a mental thing.

129
00:11:51,813 --> 00:11:57,340
It's also what we call the feeling level of an emotion, the feeling basis.

130
00:11:58,923 --> 00:12:00,865
And then we have these sankharas.

131
00:12:01,386 --> 00:12:12,884
Now, the Buddha has created these five aggregates really to point to a certain process, these sankharas, you see.

132
00:12:13,105 --> 00:12:14,807
Because that's where our problems lie.

133
00:12:15,448 --> 00:12:17,331
The other stuff is just a given.

134
00:12:18,393 --> 00:12:20,216
And the problems lie within these sankharas.

135
00:12:20,235 --> 00:12:27,106
So, you get lots of models of a human being from Freudian and so on.

136
00:12:27,322 --> 00:12:34,532
But the Buddha's model is really to keep pointing us to where the suffering arises, because that's all he's concerned with, isn't it?

137
00:12:34,732 --> 00:12:38,778
Just this problem of suffering, human suffering.

138
00:12:38,798 --> 00:12:45,505
Now when these five aggregates start moving in time, then we see much more this sort of process.

139
00:12:45,546 --> 00:12:47,509
So the five aggregates are always there,

140
00:12:47,860 --> 00:13:12,585
but we see that there are some things that are with us, as it were, all the time as a way of looking at the world and that's our Sankharas So these Sankharas, these habits mental habits which express themselves through our body language are all generated by an act of will

141
00:13:13,087 --> 00:13:21,681
And that's really where we come to this point where the Buddha is pointing to what it is that actually creates something.

142
00:13:23,044 --> 00:13:27,835
It's a very mystical thing.

143
00:13:28,777 --> 00:13:31,120
The Buddha doesn't describe will.

144
00:13:31,682 --> 00:13:33,466
I mean, it's a force.

145
00:13:33,485 --> 00:13:43,787
It's a force which manifests something into the world and it arises after an intention.

146
00:13:44,914 --> 00:13:54,499
I mean, that moment when intention becomes a flow of thought, or an intention becomes an action of speech or an action of the body, is a split second.

147
00:13:55,280 --> 00:13:59,392
Normally speaking, we don't even notice it, we just do, we just carry on.

148
00:14:00,214 --> 00:14:02,298
But that distinction is crucial, you see.

149
00:14:02,667 --> 00:14:16,322
because at the point of the arising of an intention which is only a thought flavoured with desire at that point nothing has actually happened that's a really crucial understanding because

150
00:14:16,706 --> 00:14:24,535
we would then think that every time an intention arises we've already behaved either wholesomely or unwholesomely.

151
00:14:24,556 --> 00:14:25,317
But that's not so.

152
00:14:26,379 --> 00:14:29,722
It's the arising of that intention.

153
00:14:29,783 --> 00:14:33,126
Now, the intention in the process is called tanha.

154
00:14:33,226 --> 00:14:35,950
That's what he's referring to, that point of intention.

155
00:14:36,831 --> 00:14:43,339
If it's something which is unwholesome then we have this special word, tanha, for it.

156
00:14:43,724 --> 00:14:56,206
But if it's something wholesome, then we can use the word chanda, which also has both an unwholesome or wholesome desire, but at least here we can talk about desires that are wholesome.

157
00:14:56,647 --> 00:15:01,216
And the Buddha also goes through this process.

158
00:15:01,897 --> 00:15:03,639
I mean, you don't get this written up, of course.

159
00:15:03,990 --> 00:15:06,293
But I mean, it's not as though he was an automaton.

160
00:15:06,474 --> 00:15:14,562
He was aware of what he was doing, and when he got up, when his body signaled that he was hungry, he made the intention to go out and get some alms round.

161
00:15:15,082 --> 00:15:17,985
So that wasn't something that happened automatically.

162
00:15:18,206 --> 00:15:22,932
He must have seen the intention arise, and he must have thought to himself, right, this is time to get some food.

163
00:15:24,293 --> 00:15:30,639
And he gets his bowl and his robe, and he does all the things that anybody else, that any other of his monks would do, and his nuns,

164
00:15:30,990 --> 00:15:32,251
and out he goes.

165
00:15:32,611 --> 00:15:33,592
But there's something missing.

166
00:15:33,712 --> 00:15:37,155
There's something missing from that process which does not cause him any problems.

167
00:15:39,177 --> 00:15:42,780
For us, there's something in there which is causing the problems.

168
00:15:42,801 --> 00:15:50,707
So this tanha, now this tanha, once it's arisen, we have this next thing, this upadana, this grasping.

169
00:15:51,428 --> 00:15:53,711
So what happens at that point, you see?

170
00:15:53,770 --> 00:15:54,770
What happens at that point?

171
00:15:55,331 --> 00:15:57,153
The point is a point of identity.

172
00:15:58,294 --> 00:16:00,035
The wanting becomes I want.

173
00:16:00,370 --> 00:16:10,870
And at that moment of identity, where the I comes in, the sense of me, into an action, into that flow, is the point of suffering.

174
00:16:11,592 --> 00:16:14,318
There's no suffering as long as it stays at tanna.

175
00:16:15,019 --> 00:16:21,432
So now, we can know this, for instance, in our practice, when we are

176
00:16:21,413 --> 00:16:32,687
when we're aware of some desire coming up, which we're not going to fulfill, say, when we're eating, so there's hunger there, which is not a pleasant feeling in itself.

177
00:16:33,147 --> 00:16:47,725
It's pleasant in the sense that if a thirsty person sees a water tap somewhere, then that thirst doesn't become so painful as it was if there was no water around, if you were stuck on the sea or something.

178
00:16:48,851 --> 00:16:51,837
But it's still not a pleasant sensation as such.

179
00:16:52,357 --> 00:16:55,323
Hunger is not a pleasant sensation, feeling hungry.

180
00:16:55,344 --> 00:17:06,505
So when we sit at the table and we're in contact with that hunger, and we're not reacting, we're not identifying with it, and we're not reacting to it, it is just a sensation.

181
00:17:06,825 --> 00:17:11,113
But we can describe it at that point as being unpleasant, but there's no suffering.

182
00:17:11,886 --> 00:17:12,667
There is no suffering.

183
00:17:13,028 --> 00:17:32,001
Now, if we were to carry on this fast for sixty-odd days, it would get very, very, very painful, and then the sense of hunger would become something that grasps, and we would enter into that suffering as an I, as a me, and that's the point of suffering.

184
00:17:32,102 --> 00:17:34,906
The point of suffering begins with the Upadana, you see.

185
00:17:35,208 --> 00:17:39,113
And of course, once we're in that suffering, we want to escape from it.

186
00:17:39,133 --> 00:17:45,201
So the escape is the commitment, the empowerment of that desire.

187
00:17:45,863 --> 00:17:48,185
And what that creates is an action.

188
00:17:48,606 --> 00:17:53,794
And the Buddha, in this particular stream of actions, calls that bhāva, which means becoming.

189
00:17:54,714 --> 00:18:03,207
So becoming, becoming moment after moment, driven by, in this case, an unwholesome desire,

190
00:18:03,727 --> 00:18:10,636
driven by this force, see, so it's a force, it's the will that the Buddha talks about, cetana.

191
00:18:10,656 --> 00:18:13,121
These are all included in that one moment.

192
00:18:13,442 --> 00:18:24,818
So we've got the becoming, meaning the I becomes, reinvents itself as I want, I scream, I want, I scream, I, it keeps on going, it keeps flipping around itself.

193
00:18:25,539 --> 00:18:31,167
And every time it does that, it empowers it, so it's got this force going into that desire.

194
00:18:31,537 --> 00:18:59,805
and as it's doing that, it's creating this habit, this Sankhya, it's whirling around itself and it's beginning to see that process and to see that the original problem lies in that identity that's why the Buddha is always pointing to this quality of self it's the self, you see, the point of identity which is, shall we say, the core problem

195
00:19:00,375 --> 00:19:10,789
And this core problem is deep within us because it's buried in this fundamental delusion which runs right underneath all our daily lives.

196
00:19:11,270 --> 00:19:12,813
It's just there as a given.

197
00:19:13,413 --> 00:19:14,454
I am a human being.

198
00:19:14,674 --> 00:19:17,038
Terrible delusion.

199
00:19:17,057 --> 00:19:25,650
So, committing ourselves to the human form, we're obviously committed to finding happiness in the human form.

200
00:19:25,670 --> 00:19:29,454
And that's why a lot of this mindfulness stuff, you see how it

201
00:19:29,839 --> 00:19:32,645
how it veers off towards finding happiness.

202
00:19:33,607 --> 00:19:40,340
Not that this mindfulness movement isn't a good thing, but it takes it away from the core problem.

203
00:19:41,143 --> 00:19:46,093
Mindfulness and stress relief, mindfulness and eating problems, mindfulness and good business.

204
00:19:46,411 --> 00:19:47,511
and all that sort of stuff.

205
00:19:47,612 --> 00:19:49,273
It's in big business now, you see what I mean?

206
00:19:49,694 --> 00:19:55,601
All that mindfulness is about really, you know, making the world a more pleasant place.

207
00:19:57,563 --> 00:20:06,031
But it's a goose chase because eventually it will corrupt, eventually it won't satisfy because the person keeps looking for happiness in the world.

208
00:20:07,113 --> 00:20:13,599
Now, the Buddha is actually pointing us to a different sort of happiness which is what he calls Nibbāna.

209
00:20:14,035 --> 00:20:24,872
So, in our meditation, where do we find this, where do we begin to experience this nirvanic type of happiness, you see?

210
00:20:25,712 --> 00:20:27,055
Because it's not as though we invent it.

211
00:20:27,174 --> 00:20:35,266
I remember my old teacher always saying, you know, when you get on a train to London, you don't, you know, London is not being manufactured as you take a journey there.

212
00:20:35,646 --> 00:20:38,510
London's already there, and you arrive.

213
00:20:39,673 --> 00:20:40,814
So it's the same with Nibbana.

214
00:20:40,834 --> 00:20:42,817
It's not as though we're manufacturing Nibbana.

215
00:20:42,876 --> 00:20:43,758
Nibbana's already there.

216
00:20:43,798 --> 00:20:44,960
It's staring us in the face.

217
00:20:45,540 --> 00:20:47,564
But for some reason, we can't see it.

218
00:20:47,624 --> 00:20:50,186
We can't get a handle on it.

219
00:20:51,269 --> 00:20:51,348
See?

220
00:20:51,970 --> 00:21:01,363
So, I always, usually in the evening, when I'm doing that Mahasi course, I always mention this, you know, verse from the Dhammapada.

221
00:21:01,962 --> 00:21:04,487
Those who are mindful in the presence of Nibbana.

222
00:21:04,826 --> 00:21:10,233
So, I mean, he's actually saying that, in the vicinity of, you're in the presence of Nibbana.

223
00:21:10,253 --> 00:21:16,762
So, there must be something about our meditation, especially the specific Vipassana practice, which is,

224
00:21:16,742 --> 00:21:22,190
which is taking us very close to that level of, for want of a better word, consciousness.

225
00:21:23,270 --> 00:21:25,693
It's definitely a place where there's no suffering.

226
00:21:26,394 --> 00:21:40,894
So, when you're sitting there in your practice and all sorts of things are coming up and things begin to subside a bit, and there is just that one little occasional moment of peace and stillness,

227
00:21:40,874 --> 00:21:52,809
And there is just this inner I, just this thing that keeps looking, and a sense of me looking, the observer, the observer, the observer, the knower.

228
00:21:52,829 --> 00:22:07,269
And in that particular state, after you've come out of it, or even as you hold it, just ask yourself, what is the inner state, what's the inscape of the observer?

229
00:22:08,026 --> 00:22:15,179
So this lovely word inscape, which was coined by Gerald Manley Hopkins, like you get landscape and all that sort of stuff, and seascape.

230
00:22:15,440 --> 00:22:20,347
Inscape, what is, we know through our meditation, we know the inscape of the body.

231
00:22:20,608 --> 00:22:23,914
I mean, we know what we feel, we can see our images.

232
00:22:23,934 --> 00:22:28,363
I mean, that's what the meditation makes us very alive to.

233
00:22:28,343 --> 00:22:33,211
But when you're just the knower, when you're just the feeler, what's the inscape of the knower?

234
00:22:33,292 --> 00:22:36,358
What's the inscape of the feeler?

235
00:22:36,378 --> 00:22:44,815
So, there's something about that which is pointing to a level of consciousness.

236
00:22:45,596 --> 00:22:47,319
You've got to be careful with these words, consciousness.

237
00:22:47,400 --> 00:22:48,461
A level of knowing.

238
00:22:48,711 --> 00:22:55,624
which is somehow radically different from everything else that we experience.

239
00:22:55,644 --> 00:23:01,173
And it's different in the sense that inwardly, in that inner space, nothing's arising.

240
00:23:02,295 --> 00:23:02,955
Nothing's arising.

241
00:23:03,797 --> 00:23:05,961
And if nothing's arising, nothing's passing away.

242
00:23:06,261 --> 00:23:13,433
So already, when we begin to experience that, we're actually touching upon something which is transcendent.

243
00:23:15,096 --> 00:23:28,859
Now, I only begin to talk about this in a way because a lot of the stuff that you get these days with certain types of people in the Dharma,

244
00:23:29,313 --> 00:23:47,141
is the accent on the imminent, on what's actually present, and the movement away from something which is transcendental, which is, to quote the words of Jesus, actually, Jesus Christ, to be in the world, but not of it.

245
00:23:48,143 --> 00:23:57,176
And what it does is, it stops you having this, if all you're interested in is imminence, like now, in this present moment,

246
00:23:57,510 --> 00:24:02,558
it stops you having a vision of where you're going, of where the future is.

247
00:24:02,578 --> 00:24:07,487
I mean, one can argue, well, you know, you're on the path and the future will arise, etc., etc.

248
00:24:07,866 --> 00:24:16,760
But to take away the transcendent is to bring the imminent back into this world as it is.

249
00:24:17,622 --> 00:24:25,054
And because we know the world is transient, it's very difficult to see what is imminent as not being transient.

250
00:24:27,295 --> 00:24:28,257
So that's just an aside.

251
00:24:29,137 --> 00:24:42,182
So our practice is both to see that there is only this present moment, but this present moment belongs only to the world of apparition.

252
00:24:42,803 --> 00:25:09,823
to the world of the transcendent there are no moments it doesn't belong there moments are only something that's manufactured something whereby we are able to measure what is happening now it's a time thing which is completely constructed it's not as though you don't have to have these things in the world but there's something else and it's just leaving that as a possibility that's all

253
00:25:10,816 --> 00:25:22,213
Remember, we're not into belief as such, but we are definitely into an openness, that there is that possibility of something in us which is completely transcendent of the phenomenal world.

254
00:25:22,233 --> 00:25:24,237
It just isn't part of it at all.

255
00:25:24,717 --> 00:25:28,403
And that the phenomenal world is within its scope, but it's not part of it.

256
00:25:31,150 --> 00:25:50,491
Now, you know, the basic quotations that sort of support that would be, you know, things like, there is, I mean the Buddha uses a word there which means exists, it doesn't mean like, you know, this is a book, is there exists that which is not born, doesn't die, is not conditioned, not created.

257
00:25:50,792 --> 00:25:53,196
I mean, you can't get more obvious than that.

258
00:25:53,217 --> 00:25:55,442
He talks about an āyātana.

259
00:25:55,461 --> 00:25:59,869
Āyātana is a sphere, and he talks about the sixth āyātana.

260
00:26:00,130 --> 00:26:08,065
This is another way in which he made us look at the human experience by way of consciousness.

261
00:26:08,445 --> 00:26:12,413
So these acts of cognition are limited by their sense base.

262
00:26:12,393 --> 00:26:17,644
So the eye cannot hear, and the ear can't smell, and so on and so forth.

263
00:26:18,246 --> 00:26:28,127
And all those cognitions, those acts of cognitions, based on a sense base, is an actual way of experiencing the universe.

264
00:26:28,449 --> 00:26:32,156
It's a sphere, and it's a sphere which is separate from the other spheres.

265
00:26:32,710 --> 00:26:36,954
the mind is very clever in getting all these things to happen altogether.

266
00:26:36,994 --> 00:26:46,746
So you can be watching a film and hearing what's being said and chewing your popcorn and it all seems all one fantastic moment.

267
00:26:47,286 --> 00:27:00,320
But in terms of Buddhist psychology, these are all really stroboscopic, minute little acts of cognition which come onto a screen which is happening so fast that it gives us the impression of

268
00:27:00,300 --> 00:27:05,047
of it all happening together and all in a flow.

269
00:27:05,928 --> 00:27:10,493
But the Buddha's use of the word ayatana is telling us that actually it's not.

270
00:27:10,874 --> 00:27:13,156
It's not like that at the base of perception.

271
00:27:13,376 --> 00:27:19,884
This is a trick that the mind can produce and a happy one it is, for heaven's sake.

272
00:27:19,904 --> 00:27:26,393
And another phrase that he comes to is he talks about

273
00:27:26,760 --> 00:27:28,061
Well, he's questioned.

274
00:27:28,823 --> 00:27:30,183
Somebody asks him a question.

275
00:27:30,744 --> 00:27:35,328
Where is it that the four Mahabhutas come to an end, destroy?

276
00:27:35,470 --> 00:27:43,837
Now, the Mahabhutas, of course, are your four great elements, which is how the mind experiences the body, in other words, this world.

277
00:27:44,478 --> 00:27:46,359
Where does this world come to an end?

278
00:27:46,539 --> 00:27:47,421
That's another way of saying it.

279
00:27:48,682 --> 00:27:51,724
And the Buddha says the question is wrongly put.

280
00:27:52,306 --> 00:27:56,430
It's where do these four Mahabhutas not find a footing

281
00:27:57,102 --> 00:27:58,364
not find a footing.

282
00:27:59,506 --> 00:28:01,489
Where do you not find these four Mahabhutas?

283
00:28:01,509 --> 00:28:02,911
There's not a destruction of them.

284
00:28:03,372 --> 00:28:06,497
So nothing, remember, is destroyed in the process of liberation.

285
00:28:06,636 --> 00:28:07,939
The Buddha is clear about that too.

286
00:28:08,640 --> 00:28:12,886
He says the only thing that's destroyed, annihilated, are greed, hatred and delusion.

287
00:28:15,150 --> 00:28:15,810
He says, where is it?

288
00:28:15,830 --> 00:28:20,979
He says there is a consciousness which is not touched by any of the senses, not coloured.

289
00:28:21,019 --> 00:28:24,003
The word can be translated as not coloured by any of the senses.

290
00:28:24,607 --> 00:28:35,378
which includes all the inner senses of emotions and thoughts and all that and it is boundaryless there's no boundary to it what does that tell us?

291
00:28:35,439 --> 00:28:51,273
It tells us that there's no phenomena there I mean the only reason why we're in this room is because it's bounded by these walls if there was no walls you'd have an infinite room so this consciousness doesn't have a boundary, doesn't have limitations and in all directions full of light

292
00:28:53,599 --> 00:28:55,708
And just this, he says, is the end of suffering.

293
00:28:55,728 --> 00:29:01,972
So, again, he's pointing to something in us which simply doesn't belong to this phenomenal world.

294
00:29:10,339 --> 00:29:18,032
So now this brings us to our new year, which is to do with making these intentions.

295
00:29:18,713 --> 00:29:27,147
So here, every year we have this opportunity of reflecting upon the life we've just been living and how we would like to progress.

296
00:29:28,170 --> 00:29:36,364
And this moment of resolution, you see, so Adhitana, it's one of the great perfections, one of these things that take us to the other shore,

297
00:29:36,884 --> 00:29:39,007
an adhitana, a resolution.

298
00:29:39,686 --> 00:30:03,194
Now, a resolution or a vow or a specific undertaking of this sort of nature, whether it's, you know, even on a social level, like a marriage vow, we tend to think that once you've made the resolution, that's it, you know, like it's done for life, you don't have to do it again.

299
00:30:04,609 --> 00:30:08,527
But the whole point about resolutions is that they die out, they die out very quickly.

300
00:30:09,089 --> 00:30:10,536
So the resolution, for instance,

301
00:30:10,751 --> 00:30:16,240
not to snack in between meals lasts probably half a day.

302
00:30:16,840 --> 00:30:21,807
So it's like you've got to make this special effort.

303
00:30:22,328 --> 00:30:33,664
So what a resolution is, is a point in time when you are directing yourself in life, like you're turning the ship to the north, you're directing yourself.

304
00:30:33,684 --> 00:30:36,809
But then it has to be reinforced, constantly reinforced.

305
00:30:36,789 --> 00:30:40,017
Not just every day, it's just every time it comes to mind.

306
00:30:40,337 --> 00:30:44,467
You have to remind yourself that you've made this commitment.

307
00:30:44,487 --> 00:30:45,430
Abandon all biscuits.

308
00:30:46,250 --> 00:30:47,273
You've made that commitment.

309
00:30:47,433 --> 00:30:52,285
So when you walk into a supermarket, you steer yourself away from the biscuits.

310
00:30:52,670 --> 00:31:03,826
And of course, the more this resolution takes on strength, the more the resolution gathers energy, the less the old temptations can hijack you.

311
00:31:05,188 --> 00:31:11,758
It's only when the resolution drops for a moment, then the old habits begin to take over.

312
00:31:13,409 --> 00:31:20,085
So, this resolution is a point in time where we decide to behave in a certain manner.

313
00:31:20,204 --> 00:31:23,031
It might be resolving the same thing, it doesn't really matter.

314
00:31:23,553 --> 00:31:28,144
But the point is, the power of resolution, the power of determination,

315
00:31:28,546 --> 00:31:34,451
is right there within the psychology, you see, it's right there within the grasping, the upadana.

316
00:31:34,771 --> 00:31:53,770
But here, this grasping which normally is seen as something which is deluded because it's coming from the eye, when it's not coming from that sense of delusion, you see, then at least the sense of self is working towards Nibbāna.

317
00:31:54,111 --> 00:31:57,034
So the Buddha talks about inclining to Nibbāna.

318
00:31:57,654 --> 00:32:11,094
So, when we talk about no-self, the point where all identity with this psychophysical organism has stopped, that's the point of liberation.

319
00:32:11,114 --> 00:32:17,682
But until that point, we have to keep, shall we say, amending the self.

320
00:32:18,924 --> 00:32:20,988
How do you incline towards nibbāna?

321
00:32:21,028 --> 00:32:25,114
You incline towards nibbāna by sorting out our ethics.

322
00:32:25,094 --> 00:32:29,721
So eventually, what we find is that the path is the path of relationships.

323
00:32:30,181 --> 00:32:36,990
It's how do we relate to the world, to things, to objects, how do we close the fridge door.

324
00:32:37,291 --> 00:32:38,113
See, that's important.

325
00:32:38,613 --> 00:32:43,200
And then how you relate to individuals, to people, to the earth, ecology, etc.

326
00:32:44,181 --> 00:32:50,530
So it's all to do with our relationships and what is our motivation in those relationships.

327
00:32:50,550 --> 00:32:55,017
And that's where you'll find resolutions are normally based.

328
00:32:56,818 --> 00:33:08,896
And so, when we realize that this inclined towards nothing is about ethics, you see, what we're actually doing is making this sense of self more and more happy.

329
00:33:09,837 --> 00:33:11,380
We're not trying to get rid of the self.

330
00:33:11,400 --> 00:33:14,344
If you try and get rid of the self, then you're in conflict immediately.

331
00:33:15,065 --> 00:33:18,550
What you're trying to do is make ourselves a happier self.

332
00:33:19,491 --> 00:33:23,738
And a happier self comes about through our ethical relationships.

333
00:33:24,140 --> 00:33:30,432
And then when we're really, really happy, you see, then all the stuff that makes us unhappy doesn't disturb our meditations.

334
00:33:30,773 --> 00:33:35,804
These hindrances begin to slough away because we're not feeding them.

335
00:33:35,824 --> 00:33:42,778
And it's in those, it's when, the more that we create a happy self, the more we're closer to getting rid of it.

336
00:33:43,299 --> 00:33:43,380
See?

337
00:33:44,827 --> 00:34:02,436
There's one lovely example that you might have heard me say before, but in the Mahasi center in Rangoon, so the story goes, a woman arrived and said to the teacher that her life was utterly and profoundly miserable and that she wanted to meditate and get out of this suffering.

338
00:34:03,157 --> 00:34:10,650
And as he asked her to explain this, he agreed that her life was absolutely awfully miserable.

339
00:34:11,557 --> 00:34:22,112
But he didn't say, now you've got to do vipassana, because if she'd have done vipassana, she'd probably have committed suicide, because she'd have had to go into this misery at that raw, raw meat level.

340
00:34:22,833 --> 00:34:25,536
Instead, he gets her to do this metta practice, you see.

341
00:34:25,976 --> 00:34:33,327
And through the practice of metta, she actually begins to experience these beautiful ecstatic states and realizes that happiness is possible.

342
00:34:33,927 --> 00:34:37,192
Nibbana is something beyond that, but happiness is possible.

343
00:34:37,532 --> 00:34:39,996
So, with that basis of

344
00:34:40,702 --> 00:34:49,139
confidence she begins to practice Vāsana and in no length of time, as the scriptures say, she was able to make a breakthrough.

345
00:34:49,699 --> 00:34:49,900
See?

346
00:34:50,340 --> 00:34:54,610
So, our practice, our actual practice

347
00:34:54,791 --> 00:34:57,876
is about making the self happier.

348
00:34:58,378 --> 00:35:02,083
And we ask ourselves, well, what makes me happy?

349
00:35:02,463 --> 00:35:04,407
When do I actually feel happy?

350
00:35:05,228 --> 00:35:14,083
Well, the study of happiness is now a big thing in psychology, positive psychology, for heaven's sake.

351
00:35:15,481 --> 00:35:20,630
And I think we can split it up into three types, three types of happinesses.

352
00:35:20,650 --> 00:35:23,474
There are those types which are pretty immediate and they pass away.

353
00:35:23,735 --> 00:35:36,577
Ordinary sensual pleasures, the meeting of a friend in a street and then going for a quick coffee with them and all those little fleeting moments where we experience little moments of happiness.

354
00:35:37,063 --> 00:35:43,652
And then there's those happinesses that we have where we absorb into something that really interests us.

355
00:35:43,751 --> 00:35:53,923
So it might be a DVD, it might be some hobby, gardening, it might be something where in that absorption we lose a sense of self and we lose a sense of time.

356
00:35:54,204 --> 00:35:55,324
That's always a good sign.

357
00:35:55,786 --> 00:36:01,172
And then you come out of that and you say to yourself, that was really lovely, it's a great time.

358
00:36:01,432 --> 00:36:03,695
But of course, as soon as you come out of it, you've lost it.

359
00:36:04,275 --> 00:36:06,057
The whole point of that sort of happiness

360
00:36:06,307 --> 00:36:09,331
is the absorption and the loss of self.

361
00:36:09,351 --> 00:36:23,244
And so they say that's why people do these dangerous sports, because at that point they've got to concentrate so much into the moment that there's no time for that reflection of me flying through the air with the greatest of ease.

362
00:36:26,447 --> 00:36:31,253
And as I understand it, that's what Aristotle talked about with his Eudominia.

363
00:36:32,195 --> 00:36:40,233
But the deeper happiness that gives life its propulsion, you might say, is a sense of meaning.

364
00:36:40,775 --> 00:36:50,018
And this has also been investigated by positive psychologists, that it's only when your life has an aim beyond itself

365
00:36:49,998 --> 00:36:57,188
that suddenly there is a very deep fundamental meaningfulness, which is the base of happiness.

366
00:36:57,487 --> 00:37:05,920
So long as we're working just for our little selves, we might produce these little moments, but there'll always be this underlying meaninglessness to our lives.

367
00:37:06,360 --> 00:37:08,463
It's a funny thing, but that's the way it is.

368
00:37:08,483 --> 00:37:11,668
But as soon as your life is for the purpose of somebody else,

369
00:37:12,052 --> 00:37:21,663
for the purpose of some other great aim, for the purpose of some other ideal, suddenly it takes on a deeper meaning and there you get your deep satisfaction.

370
00:37:22,103 --> 00:37:28,230
And that's why we find that people, you know, will undergo a lot of suffering for this.

371
00:37:28,831 --> 00:37:37,521
And afterwards, you know, they would say that, you know, it was meaningful, it was, you know, looking back they wouldn't have done anything else.

372
00:37:38,041 --> 00:37:40,744
You know, talk about people like, you know, people who've been

373
00:37:41,197 --> 00:38:09,262
imprisoned Nelson Mandela but these are the people that we know like Nelson Mandela and Aung San Suu Kyi and all that but there are hundreds of people who undergo torture and all sorts of things for something bigger than themselves and in that they get this real deep sense of meaningfulness and with it there is that happiness so we see that in the Buddha's own story you know when he

374
00:38:09,849 --> 00:38:12,273
At that moment when there's a great doubt, see?

375
00:38:12,873 --> 00:38:19,061
So he sat under the tree and, you know, as it's put mythically, but it's his own mind, of course, he's saying, well, you know, what's all this?

376
00:38:19,922 --> 00:38:21,144
I've been through all these teachers.

377
00:38:21,184 --> 00:38:22,365
I've got all this far.

378
00:38:22,786 --> 00:38:24,849
Nobody's discovered the end of suffering.

379
00:38:25,050 --> 00:38:27,012
Who the hell am I to try and discover it anyway?

380
00:38:27,693 --> 00:38:29,114
And how can I do it?

381
00:38:29,235 --> 00:38:30,135
How can I do it?

382
00:38:30,155 --> 00:38:30,896
And there are all these...

383
00:38:31,061 --> 00:38:34,590
great teachers and people I've worked with and they've not been able to do it.

384
00:38:34,610 --> 00:38:35,351
See, who am I?

385
00:38:35,371 --> 00:38:40,663
So you get this sense of the great doubt about me, see, about can I do it?

386
00:38:41,423 --> 00:38:44,871
And then he touches the earth goddess, you see, and the earth goddess arrives.

387
00:38:44,891 --> 00:38:47,416
And he remembers that he's not doing it just for himself.

388
00:38:47,887 --> 00:38:51,851
because in his past life he's perfected this idea of generosity.

389
00:38:52,251 --> 00:39:07,766
So it suddenly comes to his mind that this is what I'm going through, it's not just for me, it's for my family, it's for my wife, my child, for all these people and all these beautiful people I've met, and all the ugly ones too.

390
00:39:08,068 --> 00:39:17,336
And so it's that which gives him, I think, that little extra power to sit under that tree and go through that process, which couldn't have been pleasant.

391
00:39:17,889 --> 00:39:22,556
until finally he cracks it.

392
00:39:22,576 --> 00:39:38,775
So this new year is just an opportunity for us to go over these things and to see the importance of a resolution in our lives, the importance of really making these resolutions.

393
00:39:39,315 --> 00:39:47,847
Now, the downside of it is that whenever you make a resolution and you don't fulfill it, you always get this little voice saying, well, you're useless anyway.

394
00:39:48,838 --> 00:39:51,722
You couldn't keep a sausage.

395
00:39:51,742 --> 00:40:00,070
So it's a case of recognizing that that judgmental self, that self which is always trying to undermine us, has to be seen for what it is.

396
00:40:00,190 --> 00:40:02,132
It's just another mental state.

397
00:40:02,914 --> 00:40:06,396
As soon as you identify with it, then you're stuck in self-hatred.

398
00:40:06,898 --> 00:40:15,065
But as soon as you see, well, yes, you see that as judging, judging, and you separate from it, you distance from it, you see,

399
00:40:15,333 --> 00:40:17,556
And you see it for what it is and perhaps you feel it.

400
00:40:17,637 --> 00:40:22,744
You feel this sense of lack of self-worth and nobody loves me and all that.

401
00:40:23,025 --> 00:40:26,429
And you keep that and you see it and you wait for it to pass away.

402
00:40:26,449 --> 00:40:29,976
And then you regenerate your self-worth.

403
00:40:30,036 --> 00:40:34,663
You regenerate your worthiness and your inner dignity.

404
00:40:35,324 --> 00:40:38,809
Dignity, remember, comes from the Latin, which means worthy.

405
00:40:39,451 --> 00:40:40,411
Dignus, worthiness.

406
00:40:42,181 --> 00:40:48,443
So it doesn't matter how many times we stumble and fall and crack our heads.

407
00:40:48,684 --> 00:40:53,742
What's important is that we get up, dust ourselves off and start all over again.

408
00:40:54,331 --> 00:40:59,079
That's why, I'm sure you've heard me say, Fred Astaire and Ginger Rogers are my heroes.

409
00:40:59,541 --> 00:41:04,610
Because that's what he did every time he slipped on the dance floor.

410
00:41:04,630 --> 00:41:07,916
He got up, dusted himself off, and started all over again.

411
00:41:09,039 --> 00:41:16,271
So, tomorrow, when we do this contemplation, just thinking about our lives,

412
00:41:16,740 --> 00:41:29,755
just take the opportunity to look past, to look back, not simply over the past year, but a whole life, to see certain trends, certain sankaras, certain habits, certain formulations, you see.

413
00:41:30,396 --> 00:41:34,581
And see the ones that are good, you see.

414
00:41:35,521 --> 00:41:40,728
You know, we tend to have a downer on ourselves, how horrible we are and the dreadful things that can happen to us.

415
00:41:40,748 --> 00:41:45,532
But it's also really reinforcing the fact that we have lots of goodnesses in us,

416
00:41:45,782 --> 00:41:51,077
And that's why I began to institute this evening chant on joy.

417
00:41:51,097 --> 00:41:59,443
I began to realize that you're stuck on compassion, all this suffering of people, and love and all that, but you've got to generate joy as well.

418
00:41:59,463 --> 00:42:01,007
It's one of the four illimitables.

419
00:42:02,032 --> 00:42:05,818
And you generate joy by being joyful, for heaven's sake.

420
00:42:06,300 --> 00:42:18,277
And if you remember a point of joy in the day, even if it was something very simple, and you recall that and you rejoice in it, you say, that was wonderful, I really enjoyed that.

421
00:42:18,659 --> 00:42:22,284
How fortunate I am, how lucky I am to have that moment of joy.

422
00:42:22,804 --> 00:42:25,829
That in itself is cranking up the amount of joy in us.

423
00:42:26,400 --> 00:42:40,838
And when we see other people who are happy and are joyful, and our joy rises on their behalf, rejoicing in their joy, that also increases our potential for inner joy.

424
00:42:40,858 --> 00:42:48,409
So that could even be a real positive resolution, or one of them for the day, that from now on I shall develop joyfulness.

425
00:42:50,092 --> 00:42:52,697
And abandon all misery.

426
00:42:53,498 --> 00:42:56,302
So remember, all we're working with is habits.

427
00:42:56,342 --> 00:42:58,547
All we're working with is these sankaras.

428
00:42:58,567 --> 00:43:02,253
They're just habits for God's sake.

429
00:43:02,273 --> 00:43:09,704
And it's a case of when a habit arises that we perceive, we can see it's not doing us any harm, you simply don't indulge it.

430
00:43:10,157 --> 00:43:12,521
Not to indulge it doesn't mean you don't feel it.

431
00:43:12,740 --> 00:43:15,304
I mean, there's a real distinction to be made there.

432
00:43:15,324 --> 00:43:33,465
To feel a depression, to feel an anxiety, to feel an anger, to feel hatred, let's say, or jealousy, all these things have to be felt, have to be recognized, acknowledged, but you don't have to reinforce them by putting the I in there.

433
00:43:35,369 --> 00:43:37,952
And how does it, remember, how do these things reinforce?

434
00:43:38,092 --> 00:43:42,699
It's through the mind, it's through this thinking, thinking, thinking.

435
00:43:43,500 --> 00:44:00,643
So as soon as you see your thought patterns running in a way which is negative, as soon as you catch it, and see in ordinary daily life, not just here in meditation, and you actually name it for what it is, what's actually driving it, misery or hatred or whatever you see, immediately you've disengaged.

436
00:44:01,063 --> 00:44:01,784
You've disengaged.

437
00:44:02,126 --> 00:44:05,190
It cannot make things worse when it's disengaged.

438
00:44:05,170 --> 00:44:12,003
And so long as you remain at the feeling level of an emotional state, of a mental state, it's not going anywhere.

439
00:44:13,045 --> 00:44:16,192
I mean, that's a real insight that has to be understood.

440
00:44:17,255 --> 00:44:23,887
A mental state, an emotional state cannot be released except through consciousness.

441
00:44:24,322 --> 00:44:28,628
But when it's released as a feeling, it's actually exhausting itself.

442
00:44:28,949 --> 00:44:34,916
As soon as it catches into a thought pattern, it's immediately regenerating itself and generating itself more.

443
00:44:36,378 --> 00:44:44,268
So, seeing that in our meditation, in daily life, our practice is this constant effort to be awake to what the mind is leading us to.

444
00:44:44,289 --> 00:44:50,297
And as soon as you see, you're caught up in a dream, a fantasy, to actually name it for what it is.

445
00:44:51,474 --> 00:44:57,186
And then if there's time, there's possibility, you stay with it and wait for that feeling to die out.

446
00:44:57,206 --> 00:45:03,197
If there's a strong desire for something and you know it's not wholesome, you stay with it, you stay in the body, you see.

447
00:45:03,257 --> 00:45:05,320
You stay in the body as a force.

448
00:45:05,340 --> 00:45:06,724
You can feel the energy of it.

449
00:45:07,465 --> 00:45:10,429
And every time it releases that energy, it's losing its power.

450
00:45:10,951 --> 00:45:11,813
It's losing its power.

451
00:45:17,175 --> 00:45:25,873
So tomorrow I'll hand out these little sheets and I might give you a template to work on.

452
00:45:29,440 --> 00:45:31,684
Very good.

453
00:45:31,704 --> 00:45:32,164
Enough of that.

454
00:45:33,929 --> 00:45:36,653
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

455
00:45:37,135 --> 00:45:39,318
May you buy your fierce resolutions.

456
00:45:40,041 --> 00:45:47,503
A struggle always towards the end of suffering sooner rather than later.

